While in a group on the Sullon Zek test server, I found myself getting rather frustrated with the ranting of a number of different players after we had taken part in what I found to be an exhilirating PvP encounter. These players were very upset with the fact that the enemy group had attacked us while we were engaged with some bandits and the fact that they were attacking members of our group as they returned to loot there corpse. Even after I reminded them that there were no play nice rules on Sullon, and that we couldn't suffer any more experience loss being killed by mobs than by players, they continued to complain, shout, and generally carry on. I wrote it off as an unfortunate group and moved on. Imagine my suprise when a similar situation arose again with another group. And then with another. This got me to thinking that maybe we need to take a long look at what the changes in PvP means to us as players. I chose to approach this as a &quot;tactics vs exploits&quot; as I feel this is the real issue. Fair and unfair is, in my mind, a matter for roleplaying, but exploiting hurts us all (especially in PvP).<br>
<br>
Every experienced EQ player is familiar with the concept of exploits. Basically, an exploit is using a bug in the software code or a situation that does not fit with the &quot;intended world reality&quot; to gain advantage. Some examples of exploits we are currently wrestling with in PvP include, in no particular order:<br>
<br>
1) Zone line camping – attacking a character after their avatar has zoned through, but before the player has regained control of the avatar.<br>
<br>
2) Training – intentionally pulling large numbers of mobs onto another player or group with the intent of killing said player. <br>
<br>
3) NPC Guard agro range – standing outside of the guards agro radius and attacking players next to the guard with spells, missile weapons, and pets without agroing the guard. Not only does the guard not defend the victim, but they will agro on the victim if they attempt to defend themselves.<br>
<br>
4) Corpse Camping – after killing a player, waiting at the corpse for the player to return and then killing them again before they have been given a chance to recover their equipment and leave.<br>
<br>
5) Bind rushing – after being killed by another player, rushing back and immediately attacking the killer. Usually repeatedly. <br>
<br>
6) Attacking while the enemy is engaged in PvE – carry over from other PVP servers. This is considered an exploit on other servers due to the fact that the enemy will lose experience if they are killed by the mob.<br>
<br>
7) And others beyond counting…..<br>
<br>
Now on to tactics. In each of the above examples, justification within the bounds of &quot;intended world reality&quot; can be made in some situations. Or a minor variation of the &quot;exploit&quot; can gain the &quot;world reality&quot; advantage without abusing the game mechanics. Lets take them one at a time:<br>
<br>
1) Zone line camping – the delay between zone in and the player resuming control is a completely game-mechanic phenomena. There is no &quot;world reality&quot; justification for abusing this unfortunate side effect of the way the world code works. HOWEVER, many zone in points make ideal ambush points within the context of the &quot;intended world reality&quot; and should be used as such (a perfect example is the mountain pass connecting the Qeynos Hills to West Karana). The key to avoiding the zone through exploit is to NEVER do anything to affect anyone until they have taken some action after zone in (ie started running forward, began casting a spell, etc). While this is doable right at the zone line, moving off a bit tends to avoid nasty accusations.<br>
<br>
2) Training – The only &quot;world reality&quot; justification I can think of for this one is in defense of a player character city. The lack of communication between the NPC defenders of a city lead to very unrealistic situations of major invasions going on within clear view of totally unconcerned &quot;city guards&quot;.  The use of this exploit to clear a desired camp or zone lines of PCs is, however, seriously unbalancing, especially amoung those who experience virtually no risk in its use (ie characters much higher level than the zone or those employing fiegn death abilities).<br>
<br>
3) NPC Guard Agro range – simple one here, don't attack someone under the protection of a guard unless you attack the guard at the same time. Any other situation is sheer exploit of bad AI programming, no way around it. <br>
<br>
4) Corpse camping – personally I don't see this as an exploit. If I get killed by a group of bandits in West Karana, do I run up and try to loot my corpse while they stand there? If I do and they kill me again, will anyone take me seriously when I scream about being corpse camped by the bandits? Will a GM come and make them stop? The proper response to the situation would be to wait until the bandits move on or are killed by someone else, or to gather up a group of people to help me kill them so I can recover my stuff. Why should it be any different if a group of players kill me? If we can accept that the gods have removed the threat of permanent involuntary death from the world of Norrath, we must also accept that we must pay the price of our temporary deaths. That price being the loss of a little exp, any loose coin we had in our pockets at the time, and the risk of further deaths if we are not careful in planning our gear recovery. On Sullon Zek at least, this price is the same if we are foolish enough to get killed by other players or by mobs.<br>
<br>
5) Bind rushing – This becomes a tactic rather than an exploit if the person who killed you refuses your request to loot and scoot. At that point the encounter becomes exactly like a corpse recovery against mobs (see #4 above). The player or group being bind rushed is facing the same threat they would if they were trying to hold a camp in an area with rapid respawns and/or large numbers of wandering mobs. The potential for self-deleveling should reduce the use of this as a griefer exploit. <br>
<br>
6) Attacking while the enemy is engaged in PvE – lets go back to our example in number 4 above. I am fighting bandits in West Karana when a rabid grizzly wanders by. Does the grizzly continue on his way because I am busy with the bandits? Does he wait patiently for me to med up and heal before taking a chunk out of my hide? No, he dives in and makes a meal out of my scrawny corpse. It does not fit with the &quot;world reality&quot; to expect any player (except maybe a paladin) to do any differently.  As in number 5 above, the player or group trying the group must accept the risk of &quot;wandering players&quot; in the same way they accept the risk of respawns and wandering mobs. The risk of experience loss is no longer a valid argument against this perfecting logical tactic, as EVERY method of dying causes experience loss, even falling down ladders :-P<br>
<br>
7) And others beyond counting….. In my mind, a tactic becomes an exploit if the answer to either of two questions is yes: <br>
     1) Am I doing this just to piss off the other player? (ie griefing. note: I said other player, not the other character. The later is roleplaying) <br>
     2) Is what I am doing out of character with the &quot;intended world reality&quot;? (ie gaining advantage through game code quirks or bugs)<br>
<br>
In closing, the changes made to PvP on the Sullon Zek server give us the oppurtunity to re-evaluate the current PvP definitions of what is an exploit or griefing, and what is a valid &quot;intended world reality&quot; tactic. I feel we as players will miss a huge oppurtunity to improve PvP in Everquest if we simply transplant the existing rules we try to enforce on ourselves to make PvP fun as well as challenging. Verant is not the only one responsible for improving PvP, we too share that responsibility.<br>
